<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-08-07T16:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-08-07T16:00:00-05:00" n="681" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d681">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">124.613/8–150: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Embassy in the Soviet Union</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                            </seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-08-07T17:00:00-04:00">August 7,
                                    1950—5 p. m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>104. <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 257 Aug 1.<note n="1" xml:id="d681fn1">As Father Brassard had encountered continued delay
                                from the Soviet authorities in performing his religious functions,
                                the Embassy in this telegram, not printed, had asked for authority
                                to employ Father Brassard as a part time general clerk for duty in
                                the Embassy library at a stipend of $2850. (124.613/8–150)</note> As
                                <gloss target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss> aware Sov Govt on past occasions
                            has attempted to identify Rev John Brassard with <gloss target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss> and USGov. We have continued maintain position that
                            Brassard is, as were his predecessors, private Amer citizen who
                            proceeded to and resident in USSR by virtue provisions Roosevelt
                            Litvinov agreement.</p>
                        <p>
                            <gloss target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss> therefore not authorized employ
                            Brassard. Dept desires no indication be given that USGov in any way has
                            moderated its position or accepts Sov pretentions Brassard has official
                            status.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>